{{Campaignbox Gaza<U+2013>Israel conflict}}
<!-- --------------------END OF INFOBOXES-------------------- -->
'''Operation Protective Edge''' (see [[#Name|Name]] below) is an [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) offensive in the [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]] [[Gaza Strip]], launched on 8 July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishpress.com/news/breaking-news/idfs-operation-protective-edge-begins-against-gaza/2014/07/08/|title=IDF's Operation "Protective Edge" Begins Against Gaza|publisher=Jewish Press|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref> The operation follows an escalation in fighting between [[Israel]] and [[Hamas]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/09/world/middleeast/israel-steps-up-offensive-against-hamas-in-gaza.html?_r=0|title=Israel and Hamas Trade Attacks as Tension Rises|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref>

Following the [[2014 kidnapping and murder of Israeli teenagers|kidnapping and murders of three Israeli teenagers]] in mid-June 2014, the Israel Defense Forces initiated Operation Brother's Keeper in search of the three teenagers.<ref name="20140617Algemeiner">{{cite news|url=http://www.algemeiner.com/2014/06/17/idf-seizes-hundreds-of-weapons-in-nablus-as-operation-brother%E2%80%99s-keeper-enters-5th-day-video/|title=IDF Seizes Hundreds of Weapons in Nablus, as Operation 'Brother's Keeper' Enters 5th Day|date=17 June 2014|work=[[Algemeiner Journal]]|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> As part of the operation, in the following 11 days Israel arrested around 350 Palestinians,<ref name="Ahren">{{cite news | first=Raphael |last=Ahren |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/is-israels-operation-to-find-kidnapped-teens-a-war-crime/ |title=Is Israel's operation to find kidnapped teens a war crime? |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=23 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="Zitun">{{cite news |first=Yoav |last=Zitun |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4531266,00.html |title=Operation Bring Back Our Brothers: IDF arrests 200, shift focus to Nablus |publisher=[[Ynetnews]] |date=17 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="20140615TOI" /> including nearly all of Hamas' West Bank leaders.<ref>{{cite news |date=16 June 2014 |title=Watch: West Bank Hamas leadership in Israeli custody |url=http://www.jpost.com/Pillar-of-Defense/Entire-Hamas-leadership-in-West-Bank-in-Israeli-custody-some-may-be-deported-359462 |work=The Jerusalem Post}}</ref> Five Palestinians were killed during the military operation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/26/hunt-missing-israeli-boys-recriminations |title=Hunt for missing Israeli boys stirs up familiar recriminations |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2014/07/03/murder-palestinian-teen-abu-khudeir-condemned/ |title=Murder of Palestinian teen, Abu Khudeir, condemned |work=[[Daily News Egypt]] |date=3 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.ahram.org.eg/NewsContent/2/8/105345/World/Region/Israel-commited-serious-violations-in-West-Bank-op.aspx |title=Israel committed serious violations in West Bank operations: HRW |work=[[Al-Ahram]] |date=3 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/1-wounded-as-israel-arrests-10-palestinians-in-west-bank-114062600717_1.html |title=1 wounded as Israel arrests 10 Palestinians in West Bank |work=[[Business Standard]] |date=26 June 2014}}</ref>

On Saturday night July 5, an Israeli strike killed 7 Hamas militants.<ref name="Rabbani" >[[Mouin Rabbani]],
[http://www.lrb.co.uk/v36/n15/mouin-rabbani/israel-mows-the-lawn 'Israel mows the lawn,'] [[London Review of Books]] Vol. 36 No 15, 31 July 2014, p.8.</ref> In response, Hamas increased rocket attacks on Israel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21607895-hamas-wants-two-big-concessions-it-may-not-get-them-why-hamas-fires-those-rockets |title=Conditions for a ceasefire: Why Hamas fires those rockets |publisher=The Economist |date= |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> By 7 July, Hamas had fired 100 rockets from Gaza at Israeli territory and Israel had bombed several sites in Gaza.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/7/7/israel-launched-deadlyairstrikesingaza.html|title=Israel launches military offensive in Gaza |publisher=[[Al-Jazeera]] |date=7 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Noam|last=Sheizaf|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/7/8/israeli-palestinianclashesupsettingisraelifaithinstatusquo.html |title=Israeli-Palestinian clashes upsetting Israeli faith in status quo |publisher=[[Al-Jazeera]]|date=7 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.603472|type=live updates |date=7 July 2014|title=Rockets bombard south, Hamas claims responsibility |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> Early on 8 July Israel bombed 50 targets in the Gaza Strip,<ref>{{Citation|first1=Spencer|last1=Ho|first2=Yifa |last2=Yaakov|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-pounds-dozens-of-gaza-targets-in-major-counteroffensive/ |title=Israel hits Hamas, Islamic Jihad leaders after rockets land north of Tel Aviv|type=blog|newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=8 July 2014}}</ref> and [[Palestinian militant]]s increased the scale of their rocket attacks into Israel. Israel's [[Counter Rocket, Artillery, and Mortar|counter-rocket]] defense system, the [[Iron Dome]], intercepted about 30 of the rockets. Israel also thwarted a militant infiltration from the sea.<ref>{{cite web |last=Horovitz |first=David |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-pounds-dozens-of-gaza-targets-in-major-counteroffensive |title=Israel hits Hamas, Islamic Jihad leaders after rockets land north of Tel Aviv |work =The Times of Israel |date=23 December 2013 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> That same day, Hamas declared that "all Israelis" had become "legitimate targets"<ref>"[http://gulftoday.ae/portal/5b9bc7fd-ecee-4c5e-9b38-56fca9e87cdb.aspx Hamas says all Israelis will be targeted]". ''[[The Gulf Today]]''. 9 July 2014. Retrieved 17 July 2014</ref><ref>Abu Toameh, Khaled. "[http://www.jpost.com/Operation-Protective-Edge/Hamas-All-Israelis-now-targets-for-missile-attacks-361965 Hamas: All Israelis now targets for missile attacks]". ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]''. 8 July 2014. Retrieved 17 July 2014</ref> and insisted that Israel end all attacks on Gaza, release those re-arrested during the crackdown in the West Bank, lift the blockade on Gaza and return to the cease-fire conditions of 2012 as conditions for a ceasefire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=711104 |title=Hamas armed wing sets conditions for ceasefire &#124; Maan News Agency |publisher=Maannews.net |date= |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref>

On 14 July, Egypt proposed a [[cease-fire]]. The Israeli government accepted the proposal, and temporarily stopped hostilities in the morning of 15 July. However, Hamas, which said it had not been consulted on the cease-fire, rejected it in "its current form".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/07/israel-temporarily-halt-fire-gaza-strip-201471620212427540.html |title=Israel and Hamas to observe brief Gaza truce <U+2013> Middle East <U+2013> Al Jazeera English |publisher=Aljazeera.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> On 16 July, Hamas and [[Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine|Islamic Jihad]] offered Israel [[hudna|a 10-year truce]], posing 10 conditions.<ref>[http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx%3FID%3D713579 'Report: Hamas, Islamic Jihad offer 10-year truce,'] [[Ma'an News Agency]] 16 July 2014.</ref> [[US Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] would visit Egypt on July 21 to negotiate a ceasefire in Gaza.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Kerry to travel to Egypt to pursue a Ceasefire in Gaza|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/07/john-kerry-to-travel-to-egypt-to-pursue-a-ceasefire-in-gaza/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>

Operation Protective Edge is the deadliest military operation to have taken place in Gaza since the [[Gaza War]] in 2008<U+2013>09.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.middleeasteye.net/news/20-palestinians-killed-overnight-un-holds-emergency-talks-980381607 |title=20 Palestinians killed overnight as UN holds emergency talks |publisher=Middle East Eye |accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> At least 600 Palestinians have been killed.<ref name="missing"/> The [[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] estimated using preliminary information that as of 20 July nearly 72% of those killed were civilians, of whom 44% were women or children. According to the Gaza Health Ministry, over 3,008 Palestinians have been injured.<ref name="OCHA" /> As of 14 July, the Israel Defense Forces estimated that about 90 of the dead were Hamas militants, and says Hamas was using the Gazan population as "[[human shield]]s";<ref name="proposes">{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/israel-says-its-downed-drone-along-southern-coast|title=Egypt proposes cease-fire between Israel, Hamas |author=Josef Federman and Maggie Michael |work=Associated Press|date=14 July 2014}}</ref> an allegation denied by Hamas.<ref name="youtube1">Al Jazeera English <U+2013> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TydoLmhMaDo</ref> The Israeli Defense Forces reported that as of 13 July, more than 1,300 Israeli attacks have occurred, while more than 800 rockets were fired from Gaza into Israel.<ref name="voa_thousands_flee">[http://www.voanews.com/content/israel-makes-first-ground-incursion-in-gaza/1956454.html "Thousands Flee Gaza Homes Under Israel Threat"]. Voice of America, 13 July 2014</ref>

Human rights groups have argued that Palestinian rocket attacks and Israeli targeted [[House demolition in the Israeli<U+2013>Palestinian conflict|destruction of the homes]] of Hamas and other militia members violate international humanitarian law and might constitute war crimes.<ref name="btselem1">[http://www.btselem.org/gaza_strip/20140713_palestinians_killed_in_illegal_attacks_on_houses 'B'Tselem info sheet: 52 Palestinians killed in bombings of homes in Gaza Strip, which are unlawful,'] [[B'tselem]] 13 July 2014.</ref><ref name=indiscriminate>{{cite web |title=Palestine/Israel: Indiscriminate Palestinian Rocket Attacks |location=Jerusalem |date=9 July 2014 | accessdate=22 July 2014|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|url=http://www.hrw.org/news/2014/07/09/palestineisrael-indiscriminate-palestinian-rocket-attacks}}</ref><ref name="washingtonpost1">{{cite web|last=Taylor |first=Adam |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/09/roof-knocking-the-israeli-mjilitarys-tactic-of-phoning-palestinians-it-is-about-to-bomb/ |title='Roof knocking': The Israeli military's tactic of phoning Palestinians it is about to bomb |work=The Washington Post |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>

== Name ==
Literal translation of the operation's name ({{lang-he-n|<U+05DE><U+05B4><U+05D1><U+05B0><U+05E6><U+05B8><U+05E2> <U+05E6><U+05D5><U+05BC><U+05E7> <U+05D0><U+05B5><U+05D9><U+05EA><U+05B8><U+05DF>}}, ''Miv'''tza'''' Tzuk Ei'''tan''''') is "Operation Steadfast Cliff" or "Firm Cliff"; more loosely translated, "Operation Solid Rock" of "Operation Mighty Cliff";<ref name="Silverstein">{{cite web|last1=Silverstein|first1=Richard|title=Operation Solid Rock, Gaza Invasion, Begins|url=http://www.richardsilverstein.com/2014/07/07/operation-mighty-cliff-gaza-invasion-begins/|website=richardsilverstein.com|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> or "Resolute Cliff" in the form of the IDF's official Arabic translation.<ref name="Ghert-Zand" /> According to the Turkish Anadolu Agency, an Israeli military spokesman for Arab Media, Avichay Adraee, explained that the change of the operation's name in English was done to more heavily convey the idea that the operation was defensive in nature.<ref name="Ghert-Zand">{{cite web|last1=Ghert-Zand|first1=Renee|title=Name 'Protective Edge' doesn't cut it|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/name-protective-edge-doesnt-cut-it/|website=Times of Israel|accessdate=18 July 2014|date=9 July 2014}}</ref>

== Background ==
{{main|Gaza<U+2013>Israel conflict|Israeli<U+2013>Palestinian conflict}}
{{Further|Palestinian government of 2014|Operation Brother's Keeper|Mohammed Abu Khdeir|List of Palestinian rocket attacks on Israel, 2014}}
[[File:Rockets from gaza (en).png|thumbnail|Range of rockets launched from Gaza Strip]]
[[File:SderotBurningFactory1.JPG|thumbnail|Factory bursts in flames after rocket attack in [[Sderot]], [[Israel]], 28 June 2014]]

On 23 April 2014, Hamas agreed to a reconciliation deal with the other main Palestinian faction, [[Fatah]]<ref name="Rabbani" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Hamas Palestinian movement|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-13331522|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> following seven years of division. The [[Palestinian government of 2014|Palestinian unity government]] was sworn in by 2 June 2014<ref>{{cite web|last=Beaumont|first=Peter|title=Palestinian unity government of Fatah and Hamas sworn in|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/02/palestinian-unity-government-sworn-in-fatah-hamas|website=The Guardian|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref><ref name="Deal">{{cite news|last=Lyfield|first=Ben|title=Middle East peace: Deal between Palestinian political groups Fatah and Hamas casts doubt on faltering talks with Israel|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/middle-east-peace-deal-between-palestinian-political-groups-fatah-and-hamas-casts-doubt-on-faltering-talks-with-israel-9278684.html?origin=internalSearch|website=The Independant|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> and Israel announced it would not negotiate any peace deal with the new government and would push punitive measures.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dalia|first=Hatuqa|title=Palestinians form consensus government |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/06/palestinians-set-swear-unity-government-20146281348223961.html|website=Aljazeera|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> Declaring this unity will "strengthen terrorism" a day before the agreement, Benjamin Netanyahu said: "The international community must not embrace it."<ref>{{cite news|last=Daniel|first=Estrin|title=If you recognise new Palestinian government you support terrorism, Benjamin Netanyahu tells world leaders |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/if-you-recognise-palestinian-government-you-support-terrorism-benjamin-netanyahu-tells-world-leaders-9468161.html?origin=internalSearch|website=The Independent|accessdate=13 July 2014}}</ref> The agreement was likely to have a significant impact on the current round of peace talks between [[Mahmoud Abbas]]' [[Palestinian Authority]] and Israel, and shortly after the announcement of the agreement, Israel launched an airstrike in the northern Gaza Strip that injured four people, according to medical officials.<ref name="Deal" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Barzak|first=Ibrahim|agency=Associated Press|url=http://www.thedalleschronicle.com/news/2014/apr/23/gaza-official-israeli-airstrike-wounds-3/|title=Gaza official: Israeli airstrike wounds 3|website=The Dalles Chronicle|accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> Netanyahu had warned before the deal it would be incompatible with Israeli<U+2013>Palestinian peace and that Abbas has to choose between peace with Hamas and peace with Israel. When a reconciliation deal was signed opening the way to the appointment of the new government, Netanyahu chaired a security cabinet in which they voted to authorise Netanyahu to impose unspecified sanctions against the Palestinian Authority.<ref name="Deal" /> According to ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward|The Forward]]'', Brigadier General Moti Almoz, the chief spokesman of the Israeli military, said: "We have been instructed by the political echelon to hit Hamas hard."<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=J.J.|title=How Politics and Lies Triggered an Unintended War in Gaza|url=http://forward.com/articles/201764/how-politics-and-lies-triggered-an-unintended-war|work=The Forward|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref>

The operation follows a chain of events that began with the [[2014 kidnapping and murder of Israeli teenagers|abduction of three Israeli teenagers]] Naftali Fraenkel (16), Gilad Shaer (16) and Eyal Yifrah (19) in the [[West Bank]] in June 2014, for which Israel blamed [[Hamas]]. The IDF stated that the two men Israel suspects of having kidnapped the teenagers were known members of Hamas,<ref name="CBS 2014 Jun 26">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/israel-ids-2-main-suspects-in-teens-disappearance/ |title=Israel IDs 2 main suspects in teens disappearance |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=26 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |title=Operation Brother's keeper |contribution=In extended version of kidnapped teens call to police, murderers heard singing in celebration |contribution-url=http://www.jpost.com/Operation-Brothers-Keeper/In-extended-version-of-kidnapped-teens-call-to-police-murderers-heard-singing-in-celebration-361270 |newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]}}</ref> No evidence of Hamas involvement has been offered by the Israeli authorities<ref name="Islamist_group_blame">[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/israel/10901225/Hamas-kidnapping-Islamist-group-to-blame-for-youths-kidnapping-Benjamin-Netanyahu-says.html "Hamas kidnapping: Islamist group to blame for youths' 'kidnapping', Benjamin Netanyahu says"]. Robert Tait, ''The Telegraph'', 15 June 2014</ref> and high-ranking members of Hamas have denied that the group had any involvement or foreknowledge of the incident;<ref name="20140615TOI">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-rounds-up-senior-hamas-men-in-the-west-bank/ |title=Israel rounds up senior Hamas men in West Bank sweep|date=15 June 2014|work=[[The Times of Israel]]|accessdate=15 June 2014}}</ref> The alleged murderers come from the [[Qawasameh tribe|Qawasameh clan]] which is notorious for acting against Hamas's policies and its attempts to reach an [[wikt:Special:Search/entente|entente]] with Israel.<ref>Shlomi Eldar [http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/06/qawasmeh-clan-hebron-hamas-leadership-mahmoud-abbas.html 'Accused kidnappers are actually rogue Hamas branch,'] [[Al-Monitor]], June 29, 2014</ref> however, Hamas political chief Khaled Meshal said that he can neither confirm nor deny the kidnapping of the three Israelis, and congratulated the abductors.<ref name="Haaretz">{{cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/1.600759#! |title=Hamas chief lauds abductors of Israeli teens, says has no new information |work=Haaretz |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> Israeli forces killed ten Palestinians in clashes, including two under 18<ref>{{cite news |title=Middle East & Africa: Murder of three kidnapped Israeli youths has set dangerous new spate |url=http://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21606288-murder-three-kidnapped-israeli-youths-has-set-dangerous-new-spate |newspaper=The Economist}}</ref> and arrested several hundred more in the West Bank in the subsequent widespread search for the missing teenagers and suppression of Hamas cells and infrastructure dubbed [[Operation Brother's Keeper]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Yoav |last=Zitun |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4532764,00.html |title=Rescue units rushed to Hebron, searching wells and caves |publisher=[[Ynet]] |date=21 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=John B |last=Judis |url=http://www.newrepublic.com/article/118630/israel-palestine-murders-cause-criss-will-john-kerry-step |title=John Kerry's First Peace Effort in Israel and Palestine Failed, But Now He Needs to Try Again |newspaper=[[The New Republic]] |date=9 July 2014}}</ref> During the search for the three missing Israeli teenagers, the IDF arrested many of the people who had been released during the [[Gilad Shalit]] [[Gilad Shalit prisoner exchange|prisoner exchange]]. On 30 June, search teams found the bodies of the three missing teenagers in a field north-west of Hebron.<ref name="JPOST_Dead">{{cite news|title=Bodies of three kidnapped Israeli teens found in West Bank|url=http://www.jpost.com/Operation-Brothers-Keeper/Large-number-of-IDF-forces-gather-north-of-Hebron-in-search-for-kidnapped-teens-361048|work=The Jerusalem Post |date=30 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4536378,00.html |title=Security forces find missing teens' bodies in West Bank |publisher=[[Ynetnews]] |accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref> They had apparently been killed shortly after their abduction.<ref name="bo3ktf">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/bodies-of-three-kidnapped-teens-found/ |title=Bodies of three kidnapped teens found |newspaper=[[The Times of Israel]] |date=30 June 2014}}</ref>

Hours after the funeral of the three murdered Israelis, a 16-year-old Palestinian teenager named [[kidnapping and murder of Mohammed Abu Khdeir|Mohammed Abu Khdeir]] of [[Beit Hanina]] was kidnapped and burned alive in a retaliatory attack by Jewish extremists.<ref name="Sterman">{{cite news |first=Adiv |last=Sterman |title=Six Jewish extremists arrested in killing of Jerusalem teen |work=The Times of Israel |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/suspects-arrested-in-killing-of-east-jerusalem-teen/ |date=6 July 2014 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> Six Jewish suspects in the murder have been arrested by the Israeli police.<ref name="Sterman" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=710388 |title=Israel arrests suspects in murder of Palestinian teen |publisher=[[Ma'an News Agency]] |date=6 July 2014 |accessdate=July 2014}}</ref> The discovery of Khdeir's body led to protests and rioting in East Jerusalem which spread to Arab villages across the country,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/spate-of-riots-erupt-in-northern-israel/|title=Protests erupt again in East Jerusalem, southern Israel|date=6 July 2014|accessdate=10 July 2014|work=The Times of Israel}}</ref> and an official apology and condolence from Israeli prime minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/07/07/world/meast/mideast-tensions/|title=Israel calls up reservists as rockets fly|date=8 July 2014|accessdate=11 July 2014 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> Hamas, which had been credited by Israel as reining in militant rocket fire from the Gaza Strip since a ceasefire agreement in November 2012, at the conclusion of [[Operation Pillar of Defense]], took direct responsibility for a barrage of rockets fired into Israel on 7 July 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2014/0707/Ending-detente-Hamas-takes-responsibility-for-today-s-spike-in-rocket-fire-video |title=Ending d<U+00E9>tente, Hamas takes responsibility for today's spike in rocket fire (+video) |work=The Christian Science Monitor |accessdate=11 July 2014 |last=Bryant |first=Christa Case}}</ref> and insisted on the release of those rearrested as a condition of a ceasefire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/for-israel-in-gaza-a-delicate-balancing-act/ |title=For Israel in Gaza, a delicate balancing act |work=The Times of Israel |accessdate=8 July 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=714463 More than 100 Gazans killed in Israeli assault in less than 48 hours] 19 July 2014: 'Israel launched its assault on Gaza<U+2014>which it has named Operation Protective Edge<U+2014>12 days ago in what it said was an attempt to curb rocket fire from the Gaza Strip, which had increased since it began an assault on the West Bank in June that left 10 dead, 130 injured, and more than 600 Hamas-affiliated individuals in prison. That campaign was launched by Israel after the disappearance of three Israeli youth, for which it blamed Hamas but presented no evidence. Hamas, meanwhile, denied the charges, and many accused Israel of blaming the group in order to have an excuse to "crush" the group, as senior Israel officials later demanded. Although Hamas had widely observed a ceasefire with Israel put in place in 2012, as Israel massively targeted the group across the West Bank other groups began firing rockets, with Israel bombing the Strip in near nightly raids as a result, eventually escalating into the current operation 12 days ago.'</ref> At the same time, exchanges of [[List of Palestinian rocket attacks on Israel, 2014|Gaza-based rocket fire into Israel]] and Israeli airstrikes in the Gaza Strip flared.

Israel argues that this attack on the [[Gaza Strip]] is also in reaction to hundreds of rockets and mortar shell launched from Gaza by Hamas.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ho|first1=Spencer|title=Israel hits Hamas, Islamic Jihad leaders after rockets land north of Tel Aviv  Read more: Israel hits Hamas, Islamic Jihad leaders after rockets land north of Tel Aviv|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-pounds-dozens-of-gaza-targets-in-major-counteroffensive/|accessdate=21 July 2014|publisher=THE TIMES OF ISRAEL}}</ref> from Gaza Strip into Israel during a period of 19 months in 2012-14. Israel claims that the ceasefire agreement achieved at the end of [[Operation Pillar of Defense]] in November 2012 with [[Hamas]], did not prevent firing into Israel during that period.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.shabak.gov.il/English/EnTerrorData/Reports/Pages/default.aspx |title=Israeli Shin Bet (Security Agency) <U+2013> monthly report}}</ref> [[The Jerusalem Fund]], contrariwise, has listed over 220 Israeli violations of the November 2012 truce from its inception down to 6 July 2014.<ref>http://blog.thejerusalemfund.org/2012/12/israeli-ceasefire-violations-in-gaza.html "Israeli Ceasefire Violations in Gaza and World Silence." [[The Jerusalem Fund]] 12 July 2014.</ref> Hamas state that they are engaged in legitimate resistance to Israeli occupation and that attacks its military wing engaged in were a response to the IDF's violent operations across the West Bank following the kidnap and murder of three Israeli youths. According to [[Avi Shlaim]], while the "chain of action and reaction is endless", the underlying cause for the violence is Israeli occupation and colonialism in the Palestinian Territories.<ref name="AJAS">{{cite news|last1=Shlaim|first1=Avi|title=The siege of Gaza|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2014/07/war-gaza-ceasefire-201471914626128642.html|accessdate=2014-07-20|agency=Al Jazeera|date=2014-07-19}}</ref>

=== Violations of the truce ===
In the first three months after the [[Operation Pillar of Defense]], according to [[Ben White (journalist)|Ben White]], two mortar shells struck Israeli territory, while 4 Gazans were shot dead and 91 wounded by Israeli forces, which fired inside Gazan territory on 63 occasions, made 13 incursions into the Strip, and attacked the Gazan fishing fleet 30 times.<ref>[[Ben White (journalist)|Ben White]], [http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2013/02/2013220152044327694.html 'What a 'period of calm' looks like in the Occupied Territories,'] [[Al-Jazeera]] 22 February 2013.</ref> According to the Middle East Monitor, in the year following the truce, Israel violated the cease-fire nearly 120 times.<ref>Telche Abu Sulttan, [http://www.middleeastmonitor.com/articles/middle-east/12758-israel-not-hamas-is-the-serial-truce-breaker- 'Israel, not Hamas, is the serial truce breaker',] Middle East Monitor, 13 Jul 2014: "just 17 of the nearly 120 Israeli ceasefire violations over one year following the 2012 ceasefire were reported on by the ''New York Times''."</ref>
<small>Rockets and Mortars fired into Israel according to Shin Bet, Israel's security service.  The Shin Bet statistics do differentiate between rocket fire from Gaza into Israel and Gazan fire at Israeli incursions into the Gaza Strip.<ref>[http://blog.thejerusalemfund.org/2014/02/israelgaza-cease-fire-dynamics-breakdown.html 'Israel/Gaza Cease-Fire Dynamics Breakdown,'] [[The Jerusalem Fund]] 5 February 2014.</ref></small>

Rocket and Mortar Shells Launched from Gaza Strip hitting within Israel:<ref name=autogenerated4 />
